{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488636"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:50:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:50:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"498"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/498"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.43,0.06,0.08,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96893"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/498"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79508"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"432"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29931"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43960"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96893"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of gradually deteriorating vision in both eyes. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 1 diabetes. His medications include insulin and olmesartan. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His visual acuity is 6/12 in the left eye and 6/18 in the right eye. A fundoscopic assessment is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to decide the next step of his ocular management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hba1c","Optical coherence tomography","Lipid profile","Carotid ultrasound","Ocular tonometry"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fundus image shows evidence of diabetic retinopathy (DR), with dot-blot haemorrhages present. Hard exudates near the macula are suggestive of diabetic macular oedema (DMO). Given these findings and the patient\u0027s history of gradually deteriorating vision, further investigation is warranted to rule out the most common cause of decreased vision in DR, Diabetic macular oedema (DMO).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptical coherence tomography\u003C/strong\u003E (OCT) is the most appropriate investigation in this case. OCT is the gold standard for diagnosing and monitoring DMO. It provides high-resolution cross-sectional images of the retina, allowing for detailed assessment of retinal thickness and structure. In DMO, OCT typically shows retinal swelling, cystoid macular oedema, and subretinal fluid. OCT is also valuable for monitoring response to treatment, such as intravitreal anti-VEGF therapy, which is a primary treatment for DMO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EHba1c\u003C/strong\u003E, if not done recently, would be important to assess the overall management of his type 1 diabetes. It is essential to properly address and manage diabetes as a long-term goal of diabetic retinopathy management, however, would not be the most useful test to decide the next step in his ocular management. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elipid profile\u003C/strong\u003E, while important for managing cardiovascular risk in patients with diabetes, is not the most appropriate investigation for this patient\u0027s visual disturbance. While dyslipidemia can contribute to the progression of diabetic retinopathy, it is not directly related to the diagnosis or management of DMO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assess for carotid artery stenosis or plaque. It would be indicated if there were signs of carotid emboli or amaurosis fugax (transient monocular vision loss). However, the patient\u0027s gradual, bilateral vision loss is not consistent with these conditions, making carotid ultrasound unnecessary in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOcular tonometry \u003C/strong\u003Emeasures the eye\u0027s intraocular pressure, and assesses a patient\u0027s risk of glaucoma. Glaucoma can present with cupping of the optic disc, and would not show the other findings as listed above. As a result, tonometry would not be the most appropriate investigation for this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, optical coherence tomography is the most appropriate investigation for this patient with suspected diabetic macular oedema. It will provide detailed information about the extent of macular oedema, guide treatment decisions, and serve as a baseline for monitoring treatment response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Optical coherence tomography is the preferred investigation for the workup of diabetic macular oedema.","Diabetic macular oedema is characterized by retinal swelling, cystoid macular oedema, and subretinal fluid on OCT.","Intravitreal anti-VEGF therapy is a primary treatment for diabetic macular oedema."],"references":["Bowling B. Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). 2015. W B Saunders.","Virgili G, Parravano M, Evans JR, Gordon I, Lucenteforte E. Anti-vascular endothelial growth factor for diabetic macular oedema: a network meta-analysis. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2017 Jun 22;6(6):CD007419. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28639415/","Tan GS, Cheung N, Sim\u00f3 R, Cheung GCM, Wong TY. Diabetic macular oedema. The Lancet Diabetes \u0026 Endocrinology. 2017;5(2):143-55. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/landia/article/PIIS2213-8587(16)30052-3/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79508"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"498"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16893"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16893"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eeb99313-0852-4784-baf6-59ebf4914644.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eeb99313-0852-4784-baf6-59ebf4914644.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":437}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79508"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T12:18:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T13:08:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"498"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96893"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type